{{Infobox Governor |name= Alfredo Avelín |image= |imagesize=190px |order= |office= Governor of San Juan |term_start= 1999 |term_end= 2002 |lieutenant= [[Wbaldino Acosta]] |predecessor= [[Jorge Escobar]] |successor= [[Wbaldino Acosta]] |birth_date= {{birth date|df=y|1927|5|1}} |birth_place=[[San Juan Province (Argentina)|San Juan]], [[Argentina]] |death_date={{Death date and age|df=y|2012|1|26|1927|5|1}} |death_place=[[San Juan, Argentina]] |profession= Physician |party= [[Alliance for Work, Justice and Education]] |footnotes= }} '''Alfredo Avelín''' (1 May 1927 – 26 January 2012) was an Argentine politician, physician and author. He served as Governor of his province of [[San Juan Province (Argentina)|San Juan]] and as a member of the [[Argentine Senate]] and [[Argentine Chamber of Deputies|Chamber of Deputies]].
Avelín was born in San Juan Province to parents of [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] descent. He earned a medical degree at the [[National University of Córdoba|University of Córdoba]], and later founded the Colegio Médico de la Provincia. Entering politics, he founded the [[Renewal Crusade]] party. He became Mayor of the provincial capital, [[San Juan, Argentina|San Juan]], in 1958, and at the age of 31.
He was ultimately elected to the [[Argentine Chamber of Deputies]] in 1989, and to the [[Argentine Senate]], in 1992.<ref>[http://www.politicaymunicipios.com.ar/despachos.asp?cod_DES=2543&ID_Seccion=49 Politica y Municipios] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080312131741/http://www.politicaymunicipios.com.ar/despachos.asp?cod_DES=2543&ID_Seccion=49 |date=2008-03-12 }} {{es icon}}</ref>
On 16 May 1999, Avelín was elected as governor of his province with 55%, heading the list of the [[Alliance for Work, Justice and Education]], which would win the presidency of Argentina later the same year. He defeated the incumbent Governor, [[Jorge Escobar]]. His period in office was marked by economic turbulence and public unrest in San Juan, not unlike the country as a whole; by 2001, provincial employees were not being paid, and the province was insolvent.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E7D7133BF93BA25752C1A9679C8B63 ''New York Times'']</ref>
Following the downfall of the government of President [[Fernando de la Rua|de la Rua]], Avelín was a fierce opponent of the austerity measures proposed by the [[International Monetary Fund]], saying, "The only thing lacking for us is to pull down the Argentine flag and replace it with the IMF's." In 2002, Avelín was impeached and deposed as governor by a majority of provincial deputies following massive demonstrations.<ref>[http://www.lanacion.com.ar/archivo/nota.asp?nota_id=426029 ''La Nación''] {{es icon}}</ref>
Avelín considered running again for the governorship in 2007 against the incumbent, [[José Luis Gioja]].<ref>[http://www.derf.com.ar/despachos.asp?cod_des=150081&ID_Seccion=18 Derf] {{es icon}}</ref> His daughter, [[Nancy Avelín]], who also served as a senator, was eventually the candidate for the Renewal Crusade that year.
Alfredo Avelín died on 26 January 2012.<ref>[http://www.pagina12.com.ar/diario/ultimas/20-186293-2012-01-26.html Murió el exgobernador Alfredo Avelín] {{es icon}}</ref>
