'''The Feeling Nuts movement''' is a social media campaign created by Check One Two in [[London]], to encourage young men to regularly check their testicles for early signs of testicular cancer.<ref name="Age19102012">{{cite news|url=http://www.mashable.com/2014/10/01/feeling-nuts-testicular-cancer/|title=Celebrities Start #FeelingNuts for Testicular Cancer Awareness|publisher=Mashable|date=1 October 2014}}</ref> The campaign went [[viral phenomenon|viral]] when the public and celebrities began sharing pictures and videos of crotch grabs using the hashtag #feelingnuts<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/03/health/feeling-nuts-challenge/|title=Feeling Nuts Challenge for men goes viral|publisher=CNN|date=3 October 2014}}</ref> and became an annual TV event on [[Channel 4]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a597384/jack-whitehall-to-host-channel-4s-feeling-nuts.html#~pajyBFD1YWvIs2|title=Jack Whitehall to host Channel 4's Feeling Nuts|publisher=Digital Spy|date=17 September 2014}}</ref> The campaign involves both [[social media]] and television.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/news/1318751/|title=Testicular cancer awareness campaign launches comedy show|publisher= campaignlive.co.uk|date=24 October 2014}}</ref>

==Origins==
Feeling Nuts was created by brothers and founders of Salter Brothers Entertainment, Simon and Andrew Salter after being inspired by Wendy Gough, a mother who lost her son to testicular cancer in 1998 simply because he was too embarrassed to discuss it. Gough has conducted awareness talks in schools ever since her son's death which left a lasting impression on the Salter brothers.<ref name="The Independent">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/features/the-feeling-nuts-comedy-night-how-two-brothers-helped-a-bereaved-mothers-message-about-testicular-cancer-go-global-9814829.html|title=The Feeling Nuts Comedy Night: How two brothers helped a bereaved mother's message about testicular cancer go global|work=[[The Independent]]|date=23 October 2014}}</ref> They realised that raising money wasn’t necessary to stop men dying of testicular cancer and therefore created a new currency through social awareness.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Check One Two teams with Brandwatch to launch #feelingnuts campaign {{!}} Charity Digital News|url = http://www.charitydigitalnews.co.uk/2014/09/24/check-one-two-teams-with-brandwatch-to-launch-feelingnuts-campaign/|accessdate = 2015-04-23}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[The Times]]'', the brothers stated that "young guys don’t want to listen to charities lecturing them so we took a different approach" creating the social movement organisation Check One Two and devising its first campaign 'Feeling Nuts'.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/life/article4231094.ece|title = The rise of the clicktivists, the new power elite|last = Pattenden|first = Mike|date = |work = |access-date = |via = }}</ref>

In an interview with ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' Andrew explained: "Our mission is to empower people to spread awareness of this preventable cancer and change behavior to check themselves regularly. We firmly believe that this social movement, designed to save lives, will get the nation talking about this taboo subject and by using entertainment around the #feelingnuts campaign, ultimately, save lives."<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/10/23/feeling-nuts-cara-delevingne-ricky-gervais-check-one-two-pics_n_6035406.html|title = #FeelingNuts: Cara Delevingne And Ricky Gervais Lead Celebs Doing The 'Crotch Grab' For Check One Two To Raise Awareness Of Testicular Cancer (PICS)|last = Welsh|first = Danniel|date = 23 October 2014|work = |access-date = |via = }}</ref>

On 10 April 2014, Check One Two launched the hashtag #FeelingNuts to promote the Testicular Cancer Awareness Month and encouraged men to regularly check themselves for testicular cancer.

On 12 June 2014, the Check One Two YouTube channel uploaded a video titled "Are You #FeelingNuts", challenging viewers to share pictures of themselves grabbing their crotch with the hashtag #FeelingNuts to raise awareness about testicular cancer.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rc3VcIiGO7s|title = Are you #Feelingnuts?|date = 12 June 2014|accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>

The tipping point for Feeling Nuts arrived in August 2014 when the brothers dropped their trousers in [[Oxford Street]] in London and took a [[selfie]] grabbing their crotches, receiving 4,864 [[retweet]]s and 13,507 favourites on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://twitter.com/check_one_two/status/512223843130540032|title = Check One Two Twitter|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> Using #feelingnuts, they started a monthly call to action for men to check themselves regularly and then issued an online challenge to boyband [[5 Seconds Of Summer]] and [[Richard Branson]]'s son Sam Branson, who took it up.<ref name="The Independent" /> Soon more celebrities started to challenge each other including [[Hugh Jackman]], [[William Shatner]], [[Ricky Gervais]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/10/hugh-jackman-feeling-nuts|title=Feeling Nuts: Hugh Jackman Helps Raise Awareness of Testicular Cancer|publisher=Vanity Fair|date=5 October 2014}}</ref> chef [[Jamie Oliver]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/showbiz/tv/6025542/Jamie-Oliver-joins-host-of-celebrities-in-testicular-cancer-campaign-TV-special-Feeling-Nuts.html|title=What’s Jamie doing?l|publisher=The Sun|date=3 October 2014}}</ref> and super model [[Cara Delevingne]].

In October 2014 the campaign went viral and social media monitoring company [[Brandwatch]] estimated that within 3 months, the campaign had reached at least 750 million people globally in addition to thousands of media stories.<ref>[http://industry.shortyawards.com/nominee/7th_annual/oIT/feeling-nuts?category=social-good-campaign]</ref>

==The Feeling Nuts Comedy Night==
{{Infobox television|show_name = The Feeling Nuts Comedy Night|image =|caption = |genre = [[Comedy]]|director = Chris Howe|executive_producer = |creator = Check One Two|company = Fulwell 73|presenter = [[Jack Whitehall]]|channel = Channel 4|num_episodes = 1|first_aired = {{start date|2014|10|24|df=yes}}|italic_title=no}}

On 17 September 2014 it was announced that the brothers had joined forces with Channel 4 to launch an annual 90-minute comedy TV event called ''The Feeling Nuts Comedy Night'' designed to raise awareness of testicular cancer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.channel4.com/info/press/news/c4-joins-a-new-movement-dedicated-to-eradicating-testicular-cancer|title=C4 joins a new movement dedicated to eradicating testicular cancer|publisher=Channel 4|date=17 September 2014}}</ref> The inaugural show premiered on 24 October 2014 and was hosted by comedian [[Jack Whitehall]] as well as featuring comedy sketches from [[Cara Delevingne]], [[Jimmy Carr]], [[One Direction]] and musical performances from [[James Corden]] and [[Rizzle Kicks]]. The show also reunited [[Martin Clunes]] and [[Neil Morrissey]] for a new [[Men Behaving Badly]] sketch for the first time in over 15 years. The Feeling Nuts Comedy Night inaugural event was a success, easily beating and over doubling the channel’s slot average.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/ratings/feeling-nuts-comedy-night-peaks-with-900k/5079048.article|title=Feeling Nuts Comedy Night peaks with 900k|publisher=Broadcast|date=27 October 2014}}</ref>

