'''Patrick Blair''', M.D. (c.1680–1728) was a Scottish surgeon and botanist, a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] from 1712.

==Life==
He was born at [[Dundee]], where he practised as a doctor. He was introduced to [[Hans Sloane]] by [[Charles Preston (botanist)|Charles Preston]] in 1705.{{sfn|Guerrini|2004}} Being a [[nonjuring schism|nonjuror]] and [[Jacobitism|Jacobite]], he was imprisoned as a suspect at the time of the [[1715 Jacobite Rising]]. He subsequently moved to London, then settled at [[Boston, Lincolnshire]].{{sfn|Bettany|1886}}

==Works==
In 1706 Blair dissected and mounted the bones of an elephant, and contributed a description, under the title of ''Osteographia Elephantina'', to the Royal Society of London, published in 1713. He delivered some discourses before the Royal Society on the sexes of flowers.{{sfn|Bettany|1886}}

Blair published ''Miscellaneous Observations on the Practice of Physick, Anatomy, and Surgery'' in 1718, ''Botanick Essay'' in 1720, and ''Pharmaco-botanologia'' in 1723–8, which ended with the letter H. His ''Botanick Essays'' were his major work. In them he expounded the progress of the [[classification of plants]] up to his time, and the then novel views as to the [[sexual characters of flowering plants]], adding his own observations.{{sfn|Bettany|1886}}

