[[File:No smoking symbol.svg|thumb|right|150px|Enforcement of [[smoking ban]]s is strong in [[Norway]]]] '''Smoking in Norway''' is [[Smoking ban|banned]] indoors in public buildings and aboard aircraft or other means of [[public transport]].<ref name="When-you-arrive"> {{cite web | url= http://www.visitnorway.com/en/About-Norway/Travel-facts/When-you-arrive/Smoking-restrictions/ | title= Smoking restrictions | publisher= Visitnorway.com | accessdate = 2012 }} </ref> In addition, it is also illegal to smoke in outdoor locations that are close to children's schools and hospitals, also its illegal to advertise, promote or sponsor any tobacco products to the public; however, this law does not apply to tobacconist shops which are allowed to advertise tobacco related products. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tobaccocontrollaws.org/legislation/country/norway/summary|title=Norway Details {{!}} Tobacco Control Laws|website=www.tobaccocontrollaws.org|access-date=2018-12-03}}</ref>
The legal age to buy [[tobacco]] is 18 years in Norway, but 10%-12% of 15-year-olds smoke daily or weekly, and 31% of adults smoke daily or occasionally. The overall proportion of smokers is decreasing.<ref name="fact sheet"> {{cite web |url = http://www.fhi.no/eway/default.aspx?pid=238&trg=MainLeft_5976&MainArea_5811=5976:0:15,5012:1:0:0:::0:0&MainLeft_5976=5825:84434::1:5977:23:::0:0 |title = Smoking in Norway - fact sheet |publisher = Norwegian Institute of Public Health |date = 2010 |accessdate = 2012 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120502205653/http://www.fhi.no/eway/Default.aspx?pid=238 |archivedate = 2 May 2012 |df = dmy-all }} </ref>
[[Smoking in Sweden|Sweden]] was the only [[Europe]]an country to achieve the [[World Health Organization]] goal of less than 20% daily smoking prevalence among adults by year 2000.<ref name="HealthCentral">{{Cite web |url = http://www.healthcentral.com/drdean/408/60681.html |title = Quit Smoking Swedish Style |publisher = HealthCentral.com |date = 29 October 2003 |accessdate = 13 August 2010 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101112015943/http://www.healthcentral.com/drdean/408/60681.html |archivedate = 12 November 2010 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>
[[File:Snus.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Approximately 17% of adult men and 4% of adult women use [[snus]] daily or occasionally]] In Norway in 2008, approximately 17% of adult men used [[snus]] daily or occasionally, while 4% of adult women used snus daily or occasionally.<ref name="fact sheet" /> In secondary schools in 2000-2004, 21% of boys and 4% of girls used snus daily or occasionally.<ref name="fact sheet" /> Many people both smoke and use snus.<ref name="fact sheet" />
The proportion of smokers is higher among immigrants to Norway than among ethnic Norwegians.<ref name="fact sheet" /> The highest proportion of smokers can be found among immigrants from [[smoking in Turkey|Turkey]], [[Iran]], [[Vietnam]] and [[smoking in Pakistan|Pakistan]].<ref name="fact sheet" />
